Credible threat of alternative when it comes to negotiating with $NVDA, who currently charges a massive toll on top of TSMC's gross margins. 

Also if you have the size to want a custom chip, you prob also get a lot more flexibility when it comes to speed and efficiency for your own unique workflow. NVDA's chip is more one size fits all. Unless you tailor your models to NVDA's system, you'd always be a bit less than optimal, sacrificing efficiency for gains from economies of scale.

Not everyone wants their own custom silicon either. Only a handful AI labs with sufficient size or ambition do. The vast majority don't and can't. They don't even have their own models. So they'll become end users of NVidia and other custom chips. 

Ultimately, it's unclear if the custom chips will really succeed and take off. NVidia is racing to economies of scale with such enormous advantage before any custom chip can reach efficiency scale.

